email.subject: Boston Node #7: Lambda Step Functions, Dependency Graphing, and React Storybook
email.payload:
On Wednesday, February 7th at 6:00pm, Boston Node will be holding our first
meetup of 2018 and will return to WeWork in Back Bay. Join us for a great
evening of tech discussions and networking opportunities!  
  
Entry is free and we will include drinks and food thanks to our great
sponsors.  
This months's meetup brings us a variety of talks from a wide range of amazing
speakers in the Node and JS communities. Matt Williams, Dev Evangelist at
Datadog, will go through Step Functions via AWS Lambda. Jason Carter, software
dev at Simplisafe, will walk us through visualizing and organizing our
dependencies. And Andric LibreSinn, a dev at Liberty Mutual, will walk us
through React and Storybook with Markdown.  
  
We're looking forward to seeing you all there. Looking forward to this month's
meetup!  
  
\- Brian @codemouse (https://twitter.com/codemouse)  
\- Dan @danielsfields (https://twitter.com/danielsfields)  
\- Sam @hammmy_sammmy (https://twitter.com/hammmy_sammmy)  
\- Jesse @foop37 (https://twitter.com/foop37)  
  
p.s. - Please update your contact information for the Boston Node meetup group
to help with attendance and name tags when you get a chance.  
  
——  
  
Event opens at 6:00pm, talks to start around 6:50pm  
——  
  
Intro to Meetup - Welcome  
——  
  
Talk #1: Orchestrating Lambda with Step Functions with Matt Williams
(@Technovangelist (https://twitter.com/Technovangelist))  
  
OK, you have built your first Lambda function. It may even be useful (and not
just a thumbnail generator). But an application is more than a single
function; you need a lot of them. How do you get your functions working
together? In this short introduction I’ll get you started with Step Functions
and show you how easy it is to use them to orchestrate AWS Lambda.  
  
Matt Williams is one of the Evangelists at Datadog and an organizer of DevOps
Days Boston. He is passionate about the power of monitoring and metrics to
make large-scale systems stable and manageable. So he tours the country
speaking and writing about monitoring with Datadog. When he's not on the road,
he's coding.  
——  
  
Quick break ~7:30pm - 7:45pm  
——  
  
Talk #2: Dependency Graphing: Visualize to organize with Jason Carter
(@WakeStudio (https://twitter.com/WakeStudio))  
  
Jason is a software developer at SimpliSafe working on the recently launched
SimpliSafe v3 Home Security System. Works on the backend web services in
NodeJS. Previously worked at Layer3 TV which was recently acquired by TMobile.  
——  
  
Talk #3: React + Storybook + Markdown. SAY WHAT?!?!?! with Andric LibreSinn (
https://github.com/mrpotatoes )  
  
Storybook is great for creating React based components but there are some
drawbacks. In this discussion we will present a small library that allows us
to efficiently build a storybook entry for a component and keep it’s
documentation up to date at the same time!  
  
Andric is a software engineer working at Liberty Mutual. He rocks the backend
and the front end (but prefers a mix of both) and does so in JavaScript (which
is his new jam and I doesn’t think he will ever leave it). Previously he’s
worked for NPR, Christian Science and WEEI.
  
  
  
  
\--  
Please Note: If you hit " **REPLY** ", your message will be sent to
**everyone** on this mailing list (boston-node-list@meetup.com)

email.subject: A.Word.A.Day--impresario
email.payload:
impresario (im-pruh-SAR-ee-o) noun
   1. An organizer, promoter, or manager of public entertainments, such as
      a ballet, opera, concert, or theater company.
   2. Any manager or director.
[From Italian impresario (one who undertakes a business), from impresa
(undertaking), from imprendere (to undertake).]
   "Even on Broadway, few stars have crashed as spectacularly as Garth
   Drabinsky, the impresario behind Ragtime, theatreland's highest-grossing
   show."
   From Riches to Ragtime, The Economist (London), Aug 15, 1998.
"All the world's a stage, / And the men and women merely players: / They
have their exits and their entrances; / And one man in his time plays
many parts." So wrote our friend Bill Shakespeare some 400 years ago in
one of his most profound observations on human condition. Yet, we often
treat this life as if we really are the people we're playing. Imagine how
few troubles we might have if we remember it's only a role we are playing.
All we need to do is to play it as best we can and then gracefully exit
the stage.                                                         -Anu

email.subject: A.Word.A.Day--kilkenny cats
email.payload:
kilkenny cats (kil-KEN-ee kats) noun
   People who fight relentlessly till their end.
[From a pair of proverbial cats in Kilkenny who fought till only their tails
were left.]
According to a story, some people in the town of Kilkenny in Ireland enjoyed
tying the tails of two cats and watching them fight till only their tales
were left behind. Most likely the story is a parable of a contest between
Kilkenny and Irishtown, two municipalities which fought about their boundaries
till little more than their tails were left. Here is a popular limerick
(another word that takes its origins from the name of an Irish town) about
the cats:
"There wanst was two cats of Kilkenny
Each cat thought there was one cat too many
So they fought and they fit
And they scratched and they bit
'Til instead of two cats there weren't any."
   "When Lord Cranborne placed Hatfield House at the disposal of Unionists
   to talk things through in November 1997, the result was a meeting after
   the style of the fighting Kilkenny cats."
   A Man of Parts, The Economist (London), Apr 15, 2000.
This week's theme: toponyms or words derived from place names.
